    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a great start for the students. To make it a bit more of a debate for the class, could you add a section explaining the different legal perspectives on this? I want to show them the side that argues for a more limited, procedural approach to due process so they can see the tension between those two ways of interpreting the Constitution.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The argument for a strictly procedural view of due process is a conservative one, insisting that the Constitution only guarantees fair *methods* of lawmaking, not specific outcomes. Proponents of this limited view fear that substantive due process is judicial activism, allowing unelected judges to substitute their personal policy preferences for those of the elected legislature. They argue that if the government follows the rules, its laws should stand, regardless of how liberal or conservative the outcome is.",
      "source": "target",
